Chapter 5: The Static Mask
The silence that followed the implosion was louder than Jax’s screaming. The yellow fog swirled back into the space where the creature had been, indifferent and thick.
"Ren?" Mira’s voice was barely a breath. She lowered her staff, the tip clicking against the concrete. "Your hand... I saw... it just vanished."
Ren quickly closed his fist, pulling his sleeve down over the silver geometric pattern. The floating text boxes over their heads—the status bars for Jax and Mira—flickered and dimmed, but didn't disappear.
[Warning: Sync Rate 88%. Maintain composure to prevent Essence detection.]
"It must have been unstable," Ren said. He surprised himself with how steady his voice was. "I told you the dampener on the dummy in the hall was misaligned. This thing... it was a high-density mass. When Jax hit it with that much kinetic force, it reached a critical state. It collapsed on itself."
"Collapsed?" Jax was on the ground, clutching his numbing arm. He looked up, his eyes bloodshot. "It was eating me, Ren. I felt it... it wasn't just cold. It was like I didn't exist for a second."
"Physics, Jax," Ren said, stepping forward to help him up. He made sure to use his left hand—the one without the mark. "The vacuum created by a collapsing Void-core is intense. You're lucky your armor took the brunt of the pressure."
Jax stared at Ren’s hand, then at the empty floor. The arrogance was gone, replaced by a hollow, flickering fear.
"Yeah," Jax muttered, leaning heavily on Ren. "Physics. Right."
